<doc id="42595" wikidata="Q7669422" url="?curid=42595" title="TAT-6">
<text>TAT-6 was the sixth transatlantic telephone cable. It was in operation from 1976 to 1994, with a bandwidth of 12MHz (4,000 telephone circuits) between Green Hill (United States) and Saint-Hilaire-de-Riez, Vendée, (France).

Known as the SG coaxial cable system, designed by Bell Labs, the cable is with repeater spacing of .
The deep sea portion, some in length, was laid by the Cable Ship &quot;Long Lines&quot;, owned by AT&amp;T. Portions of the shore sections were laid by the French Cable Ship &quot;Vercors&quot;.

The SG Undersea Cable System was designed by Bell Laboratories at their Allentown, PA, Greensboro, NC, Holmdel, NJ, and Whippany, NJ facilities.

A few years later, TAT-7 was put into service between Tuckerton, New Jersey, and Lands End, England, and was the last analog Transatlantic undersea system.

The following system, TAT-8, was implemented by AT&amp;T Corp. (with Bell Laboratories), STC (with British Telecom), and Alcatel (with France Telecom). This was the first Transatlantic fiber-optic system, had greatly increased capacity and performance.

